{{Infobox royalty| name = Johann George II | image =Johan Georg II Johann Fink, vor 1675.jpg | caption = Portrait by Johann Finck, 1675. | succession = [[Elector of Saxony]] | reign =8 October 1656 – 22 August 1680 | predecessor =[[John George I, Elector of Saxony|John George I]] | successor =[[John George III, Elector of Saxony|John George III]] | birth_date ={{birth date|1613|5|31|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Dresden]] | death_date ={{death date and age|1680|8|22|1613|5|31|df=y}} | death_place = [[Tübingen]] | spouse =[[Magdalene Sybille of Brandenburg-Bayreuth]] | issue =[[John George III, Elector of Saxony]] | full name = | house =[[House of Wettin]] | father =[[John George I, Elector of Saxony]] | mother =[[Magdalene Sibylle of Prussia|Magdalene Sybille of Prussia]] | religion= [[Lutheran]] |monarch | image_size = 200px | place of burial=[[Cathedral of Freiberg]] |}} '''Johann George II''' (31 May 1613 – 22 August 1680) was the [[Elector of Saxony]] from 1656 to 1680. He belonged to the Albertine line of the [[House of Wettin]].
==Biography== [[File:John George II, Elector of Saxony (1613–1680) - Order of the Garter stall plate - St George's Chapel.png|thumb|left|17th century Order of the Garter stall plate for John George II, Elector of Saxony. Located in St. George's Chapel, Windsor Castle, Berkshire, England]] He was the third (fourth in order of birth){{citation needed|date=November 2012}} but eldest surviving son of the Elector [[John George I, Elector of Saxony|Johann George I, Elector of Saxony]]{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=459}} and [[Magdalene Sibylle of Prussia|Magdalene Sybille of Prussia]], his second spouse.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}} He succeeded his father as Elector of Saxony when John George I died on 8 October 1656.<ref>See the Encyclopædia Britannica article on John George I for his date of death—immediately before the article on John George II {{harv|Chisholm|1911|p=459}}.</ref>
In 1657 John George made an arrangement with his three brothers with the object of preventing disputes over their separate territories, and in 1664 he entered into friendly relations with [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]. He received money from the French king, but the existence of a strong anti-French party in Saxony induced him occasionally to respond to the overtures of the emperor [[Leopold I, Holy Roman Emperor|Leopold I]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=459}}
[[Image:Johann Georg II.jpg|thumb|right|240px|John George II, picture from 1658.]] The elector's primary interests were not in politics, but in music and art. He adorned [[Dresden]], which under him became the musical centre of Germany; welcoming foreign musicians and others he gathered around him a large and splendid court, and his capital was the constant scene of musical and other festivals.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=459}} He commissioned the building of the first opera house, the [[Opernhaus am Taschenberg]].
In 1658 John George was accepted into the [[Fruitbearing Society]], through the patronage of Duke [[Wilhelm, Duke of Saxe-Weimar|William of Saxe-Weimar]].{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}<!--for the whole paragraph-->
His enormous expenditure on the arts compelled John George in 1661 to grant greater control over monetary matters to the estates, a step which laid the foundation of the later system of finance in Saxony. Also, his government was less effective in establishing [[Absolutism (European history)|absolutist]] rule and a [[standing army]] than were [[Bohemia]] or [[Prussia]].{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=459}}
John George's reign saw the slow [[economic reconstruction]] of Saxony after the [[Thirty Years' War]]. New trades and [[manufacture]]s developed, such as textiles, hard coal and glass. Locally mined silver filled the Electorate's empty treasury, and the [[Leipzig Trade Fair]] and the Bohemian ''Exulanten'' of 1654 also stimulated economic activity.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}<!--for the whole paragraph-->
John George died in [[Freiberg]] on 22 August 1680.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=459}}
==Family== In [[Dresden]] on 13 November 1638 John George married [[Magdalene Sybille of Brandenburg-Bayreuth|Magdalene Sibylle of Brandenburg-Bayreuth]]. They had three children:{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}
#Sibylle Marie (16 September 1642 – 27 February 1643) #Erdmuthe Sophie (25 February 1644 – 22 June 1670), married on 29 October 1662 to [[Christian Ernst, Margrave of Brandenburg-Bayreuth]] #[[John George III, Elector of Saxony|John George III]] (20 June 1647 – 12 September 1691), his successor as Elector.
